      <hedline>
        <hl1>Etymologies</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Paul Siff letter disputes Michael Hanchard's September 3 letter on etymological origin of word miscegenation (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Michael Hanchard [Letters, Sept. 3] is wrong on the etymological origin of the word miscegenation. It is derived from the Latin miscere (to mix) and genus (race). Thus, it simply means ''racial mixing''; any negative connotation is extraneous to its etymology. The mistake is a common one, and may stem from misidentifying the word's prefix as ''mis'' rather than ''misc.''</p>
        <p>PAUL SIFF  Fairfield, Conn.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
